{"title_page": "Richard A. Teague", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name           = Richard A. Teague\n| image          = Richard A Teague Foto.jpg\n| image_size     = \n| alt            = Man in a suit looking at camera while sitting at a desk\n| caption        = Richard Teague at AMC during the 1970s\n| birth_name     = \n| birth_date     = {{Birth date|1923|12|26}}\n| birth_place    = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], United States\n| death_date     = {{Death date and age|1991|05|05|1923|12|26}}<ref name=\"cp34\">{{cite journal|title=Obituaries |journal=Cars & Parts |publisher=Amos Press |volume=34 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=PkxWAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Richard+Teague%22+AMC |accessdate=27 August 2013}}</ref>\n| death_place    = [[San Diego]], California, United States\n| death_cause    = \n| education      = \n| alma_mater     = [[ArtCenter College of Design]]\n| occupation     = Industrial designer\n| years_active   = 1948\u20131983\n| employer       = [[General Motors]]<br/>[[Packard Motor Car Company]]<br/>[[Chrysler Corporation]]<br/>[[American Motors Corporation]]\n| known_for      = Developing the concept of interchangeable body panels for use among different models\n| notable_works  = 1955 [[Packard Patrician#1955\u20131956|Packard]]<br/>[[Oldsmobile#1950s styling|Oldsmobile Rocket]]<br/>[[Rambler Classic]]<br/>[[AMC Cavalier]]<br/>[[AMC Gremlin]]<br/>[[AMC Javelin]]<br/>[[AMC AMX]]<br/>[[AMC AMX-GT|AMX GT]]<br/>[[AMC Hornet]]<br/>[[AMC Eagle]]<br/>[[Jeep Cherokee (XJ)]]<br/>[[AMC Pacer]]\n| awards         = [[EyesOn Design]] Lifetime Design Achievement <br/> ''[[Automotive Industries (magazine)|Automotive Industries]] '' Man of the Year\n}}\n\n'''Richard A. \"Dick\" Teague''' (December 26, 1923 \u2013 May 5, 1991) was an American industrial designer in the North American automotive industry. He held [[automotive design]] positions at [[General Motors]], [[Packard]], and [[Chrysler]] before becoming Vice President of Design for [[American Motors|American Motors Corporation]] (AMC), and designed several notable show cars and production vehicles including AMC's [[AMC Pacer|Pacer]], [[AMC Gremlin|Gremlin]] and [[AMC Hornet|Hornet]] models, as well as the [[Jeep Cherokee (XJ)|Jeep Cherokee XJ]] and either designed assisted in the designing of later cars for Chrysler such as the [[Jeep Grand Cherokee]] and [[Dodge Neon|Neon]] after American Motors' buyout.\n\n==Early life==\nTeague's mother worked in the motion picture industry during the silent movie era.<ref name=\"aq1992\">{{cite journal|title=Dick Teague |journal=Automobile Quarterly |volume=30 |issue=2 |page=6 |year=1992 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=7D1WAAAAMAAJ&q=Dixie+Duval+Our+Gang |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> At five years of age Teague appeared in five episodes of ''[[Our Gang]]'', playing the role of Dixie Duval, a girl.<ref name=\"ward\">{{cite book|last=Ward |first=James Arthur |title=The fall of the Packard Motor Car Company |year=1995 |publisher=Stanford University Press |isbn=978-0-8047-2457-9 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=7D11a-EPzwMC&pg=PA177&dq=Richard+A.+Teague |page=177 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> When he was six, he was seriously injured in a car accident near [[Pasadena, California]], which was caused by a [[Driving under the influence|drunk driver]]. He lost several teeth, suffered a broken jaw, as well as sight in his right eye (leaving him without depth perception or stereoscopic vision), while his mother was left an invalid.<ref name=\"aq1992\"/><ref name=\"coachbuilt\">{{cite web|url=http://www.coachbuilt.com/des/t/teague/teague.htm |title=Richard (Dick) A. Teague 1923\u20131991 |publisher=Coacbuilt |year=2004 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> A year later his father was killed in another automobile accident, also caused by a drunk driver.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Racina |first=Thom |title=Car Man |journal=Westways |year=1975 |volume=67 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=FdO2AAAAIAAJ&q=Teague+Pasadena+A+year+later+his+father+was+killed+in+an+automobile+accident |page=53 |publisher=Automobile Club of Southern California |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref>\n\nWhile attending grade school in Los Angeles during the 1930s, Teague built model airplanes before turning to [[hot rod]]s, since his schoolmates included [[Ed Iskenderian|Ed Iskendarian (who became a drag racer)]], and land speed racer [[Stuart Hilborn]], as well as other car enthusiasts.<ref name=\"coachbuilt\"/><ref name=\"hubgarage\">{{cite web|url= http://www.hubgarage.com/mygarage/proto72/blogs/25991 |first=Adam |last=Icenogle |title=Richard Teague (1923 \u2013 1991) |publisher=Hub Garage |year=1998 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> He participated in time trials on a dry lake northeast of Los Angeles and was fond of saying that he \"had a little gasoline in his blood.\"<ref name=\"coachbuilt\"/>\n\nTeague was exempt from service in the armed forces during [[World War II]] because of his visual impairment.<ref name=\"ward\"/> After graduating from [[Susan Miller Dorsey High School]] in 1942, he worked as an aircraft technical illustrator for [[Northrop Corporation]].<ref name=\"coachbuilt\"/> His boss, Paul Browne, was a former designer at [[General Motors]] who suggested that Teague take night classes at the [[ArtCenter College of Design]].\n\n==Early work==\n[[File:Packard Executive Hardtop 1956.jpg|thumb|The last Teague design for Packard, the [[Packard Executive|Executive]]]]\nAfter [[World War II]], Teague penned a design for a pre-[[Henry J]] economy car for [[Kaiser Motors]]. In 1947 he joined the General Motors design studios<ref name=\"ward\"/> headed by Edmund Anderson. Starting as an [[apprentice]] stylist and eventually graduating to the [[Cadillac]] advanced design group, he also worked on the 1950 [[Oldsmobile#1950s styling|Oldsmobile Rocket]]. The 1950s \"saw some of the most beautiful and some of the most outlandish vehicles\" and the head of the design department at General Motors liked chrome on cars.<ref name=\"earl\">{{cite news|url= http://apps.detnews.com/apps/history/index.php?id=101 |last=Baulch |first=Vivian M. |title=Harley Earl, father of the 'dream' car |newspaper=The Detroit News |date=25 September 1998 |archiveurl= https://archive.is/20120808112650/http://apps.detnews.com/apps/history/index.php?id=101 |archivedate=8 August 2012 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> Teague described how two sets of overlay designs were made for [[Harley Earl]] to choose from. Both chrome trim sets had been put on one Oldsmobile prototype by mistake. Earl saw it and ordered it produced that way although the stylists were horrified.<ref name=\"earl\"/>\n\nTeague was dismissed from General Motors in 1952, and joined the [[Packard|Packard Motor Car Company]]<ref name=\"ward\"/> as Chief Stylist, following John Reinhart's resignation. His first work there was a minor facelift on the Packard line for 1953, and when the Packard management under [[James J. Nance]] decided to re-launch the Clipper brand as a stand-alone make, separate from Packard, it was Teague who achieved the visual distinction between the two. He also designed several Packard [[show car]]s.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/13/automobiles/collectibles/13LIST.html |title=Packard Dreams: The 7 Postwar Concept Cars |first=Fred|last=Hailer|newspaper=The New York Times |date=10 September 2009 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> These included the 1953 Balboa<ref name=\"dorrington\">{{cite journal|url= http://www.autoquarterly.com/featured_articles/article.php?id=9 |title=Packard Conceptualized |first=Leigh |last=Dorrington |journal=Automobile Quarterly |volume=50 |issue=1 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> (whose canopied reverse-slant and lowering for ventilation rear window<ref>{{cite journal|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=JNwDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA97&lpg=PA97&dq=Hudson+and+Packard+Present+Their+Cars+of+the+Future |page=97 |title=Hudson and Packard Present Their Cars of the Future |journal=Popular Mechanics |date=November 1953 |volume=100 |issue=5 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> later appeared on the 1957 [[Mercury Turnpike Cruiser]], 1958\u20131960 [[Lincoln Continental]], and various Mercury models), the 1954 Panther,<ref name=\"dorrington\"/> and contributed with William Schmidt to the 1955 Request, whose principal designer was Dick Macadam.<ref name=\"dorrington\"/>\n\nThe restyled Packard line for 1955 showed Teague's keen eye for detail and his ability to produce significant changes based on limited budgets. However, the company was not doing well following the purchase of struggling [[Studebaker]] Corporation in 1954. The last Teague design for Packard was the [[Packard Executive|Executive]], introduced mid-1956 and derived from the Clipper Custom, launched just as sales of the luxury Packard line collapsed. Teague also designed the last Packard show car, the Predictor, plus a new Packard and Clipper lineup for 1957 that would have followed the general lines of the Predictor. The design was stillborn when the Detroit Packard operations were shut down completely in mid-1956. Lacking funds for all-new models, the Studebaker-Packard Corporation had to make use of existing and economical Studebaker designs. Working with little time and money, the stopgap 1957 Studebaker-based Packard models became known as \"Packardbakers.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://auto.howstuffworks.com/1957-1958-packardbaker.htm |title=1957\u20131958 Packardbaker |author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide''|publisher=auto.howstuffworks.com |date=31 October 2007 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> The 1957 Packard Clipper, popularly derided as \"a Studebaker wearing Packard makeup\", was designed largely by Teague, and was intended as a temporary stopgap to keep the brand going until the company's fortunes improved and a \"real\" Packard model could again be made.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://auto.howstuffworks.com/1957-1958-packardbaker1.htm |title=Design of the 1957\u20131958 Packardbaker |author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide'' |publisher=auto.howstuffworks.com |date=31 October 2007 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref>\n\nBy 1957, the entire Packard styling team had moved to [[Chrysler Corporation]] and Teague became Chief Stylist.<ref name=\"century\">{{cite book |title=A century of automotive style: 100 years of American car design |page=202 |first=Michael |last=Lamm |first2=Dave |last2=Holls |year=1996 |publisher=Lamm-Morada |isbn= 9780932128072 }}</ref> After leaving due to management conflicts, he went to work for an independent design firm on non-automotive assignments.\n\n==American Motors==\n[[File:1961 AMC PRfoto Designers.jpg|thumb|AMC designers, 1961: Teague stands by the scale model Rambler's left front fender]]\n<!-- FAIR USE of 1961 AMC PRfoto Designers.jpg: see image description page at http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:1961 AMC PRfoto Designers.jpg for rationale -->\n[[File:1967 Ambassador DPL conv top-down-winter-FL palm.jpg|thumb|1967 AMC Ambassador convertible]]\n[[File:AMC Pacer 1975-1978.jpg|thumb|AMC Pacer 1975]]\n[[File:XJ Mossgreen.png|thumb|One of Teague's widely known designs, the Jeep Cherokee XJ 1983]]\n\nTeague joined [[American Motors Corporation]] (AMC) as a member of [[Edmund E. Anderson]]'s design team in 1959, and became principal designer when Anderson left in 1961. Teague's first assignment, according to designer James W. (Jim) Alexander, was to re-do the front sheetmetal on the 1961 [[AMC Ambassador|Ambassador]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=VO8mAQAAMAAJ&q=first+assignment,+according+to+designer+James+W.+(Jim)+Alexander,+was+to+re-do+the+front+sheetmetal+on+the+1961+Ambassador Lamm, p. 202. Retrieved on 27 August 2013]</ref> The first cars influenced by Teague's styling were the 1963 [[Rambler Classic]] and Ambassador, AMC's first all-new models since 1956.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.canada.com/nationalpost/news/driving/story.html?id=63b38ace-dd81-436e-a781-279b22f10aab |last=Vance |first=Bill |title=Classic kept AMC in the auto game: 1963 AMC Rambler Classic |newspaper=National Post |date=28 July 2006 |accessdate=27 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103122644/http://www.canada.com/nationalpost/news/driving/story.html?id=63b38ace-dd81-436e-a781-279b22f10aab |archivedate=3 November 2012 }}</ref> With the ascendancy of Teague in the early 1960s, \"AMC Styling began to be written of in a more positive manner\" within the industry and automotive press.<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=BPqI4GNSPNQC&pg=PR5&dq=Richard+A.+Teague |page=v |title=The Nash Styling Sketchbook |first=Patrick R. |last=Foster |publisher=Olde Milford Press |year=1998 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref>\n\nTeague was Vice President at the automaker from 1964 until he retired from AMC in 1983. At his retirement, he joked that the only [[Detroit, Michigan|Detroit]] auto company he had not worked for was [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]].<ref name=\"Wards Automotive News\">{{cite journal|first=David|last=Smith|title=Dick Teague Ends Record Tenure In Style |journal=Wards Automotive News |date=February 1985 |url= http://www.planethoustonamx.com/main/dick%20teague%20retires.htm |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101127012656/http://planethoustonamx.com/main/dick%20teague%20retires.htm |archivedate=27 November 2010 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref>\n\nAlthough he worked within tight budget restrictions at AMC, Teague sometimes referred to his times there as \"[[Camelot]]\". Designing several different cars from existing AMC stampings, he worked \"relative miracles\" compared to the spending norms in this industry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brophy.com/eodweb/htmls/designers/hd99_1.htm |title=Richard A. Teague: A friend writes of Teague's warmth, ability, and ingenuity |publisher=Brophy Marketing Services |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080511144724/http://www.brophy.com/eodweb/htmls/designers/hd99_1.htm |archivedate=11 May 2008 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref>  With little money to work with, he reconfigured the existing cars and parts in new ways.<ref name=\"hine\">{{cite book|last=Hine |first=Thomas |title=The Great Funk: Falling Apart and Coming Together (on a Shag Rug) in the Seventies |publisher=Farrar, Straus and Giroux |year=2007 |url= https://archive.org/details/greatfunkfalling0000hine |url-access=registration |quote=richard a. teague. |pages=[https://archive.org/details/greatfunkfalling0000hine/page/41 41]\u201342 |isbn=978-0-374-14839-3 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> For example, he incorporated the doors from AMC's large-sized automobiles into his design for the new 1964 compact [[Rambler American]].\n\nThe [[AMC Cavalier]] was one of the \"Project IV\" concept cars in the mid-1960s that demonstrated advanced techniques of interchangeable body panels and design [[symmetry]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Bell |first=Jonathan |title=Concept Car Design: Driving the Dream |publisher=Rotovision |year=2003 |page=67 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=REQgF0IomccC&pg=PA67&dq=AMC+Cavalier |isbn=978-2-88046-564-3 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> The right front and left rear fenders were identical, as well as the panels for doors, hood, and deck lid all interchanged. The [[automobile platform]]s designed by Teague featured numerous interchangeable door skins, glass, and more. For example, the front and rear bumpers on the 1970 AMC Hornet were made from the same stamping. This design talent yielded significant cost savings for the company.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Irwin |first=Robert W. |title=Detroit Listening Post |journal=Popular Mechanics |volume=126 |issue=3 |page=30 |date=September 1966 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=stMDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA30&dq=AMC+Cavalier |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref>\n\nTeague's work on the 1967-1969 [[AMC Ambassador]] proved that he \"could do more with less than most any other car designer around -- usually because he had to.\"<ref name=\"ambassador-67-68-69\">{{cite web|url= http://auto.howstuffworks.com/1967-1969-amc-ambassador.htm |title=1967, 1968, 1969 AMC Ambassador |author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide'' |publisher=auto.howstuffworks.com |date=27 November 2007 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> While the 1965 models were reskinned  and rode on a longer wheelbase, Teague \"came through handsomely with crisp, angular lines\" that helped the Ambassador achieve record sales.<ref name=\"ambassador-67-68-69\"/> The 1967 model year brought even greater change, in line with Roy Abernethy's longtime aim of matching Big Three models on most every front, including an all-new Ambassador that \"emerged as one of the decade's unsung good-lookers.\"<ref name=\"ambassador-67-68-69\"/>\n\nAfter a management change at AMC, Teague worked under [[Roy D. Chapin, Jr.]] who was also a [[sports car]] enthusiast.<ref name=\"mueller99\">{{cite book|last=Mueller |first=Mike |title=Motor City Muscle: The High-Powered History of the American Muscle Car |publisher=MBI Publishing |year=1997 |page=99 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZLP8kKL4w2kC&pg=PA101&dq=1968+Javelin+born+out+of+AMX |isbn=978-0-7603-0196-8 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> Teague developed production models that featured \"excitement\" such as the [[AMC Javelin|Javelin]]. This design evolved from two AMX prototypes that were part of the \"Project IV\" concept cars during 1966.<ref>Mueller, page 101.</ref> Other top executives, such as [[Robert B. Evans]], wanted Teague's two-seat [[AMC AMX|AMX]] design to be brought to the market \"very quickly.\"<ref name=\"mueller99\"/> Teague originated a non-running show car in late-1965 and since he was a \u201ctwo-seater kind of guy, the production American Motors AMX was his car.\"<ref name=\"stuffAMX\">{{cite web|url= http://auto.howstuffworks.com/american-motors-sports-cars.htm |author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide''|publisher=auto.howstuffworks.com |date=15 May 2007 |title=American Motors AMX |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> The new models offerings reflected AMC's strategy to shed its \"economy car\" image and appeal to a more youthful, performance-oriented market.<ref name=\"mueller99\"/>\n\nDuring the 1970s, \"only a handful of cars had real personalities, and many of those came from the smallest U.S. producer, American Motors\" under the direction of Teague.<ref name=\"hine\"/>\n\nWhen the automobile market was changing to a greater focus on quality and fuel efficiency, Teague characterized the work by his design team at AMC as \"we still want to make cars with charisma; cars that stand out from the pack ... the future means the large look inside, away from the claustrophobic.\"<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Chilton's Iron Age |page=130 |volume=223 |year=1980 |title=Automobile manufacturing |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=23JWAAAAMAAJ&q=Teague+Jeep+design&dq=Teague+Jeep+design |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref>\n\nTeague worked on the design of the 1975 AMC Pacer, the first car with [[cab forward]] design.<ref name=\"coachbuilt\"/> It was also the first 'wide-small' automobile that \"gave drivers the impression they were driving a conventional large American.\"<ref name=\"vance-pacer\">{{cite web|url= http://thechronicleherald.ca/wheelsnews/570822-wheels-classic-cars-the-american-motors-pacer |first=Bill |last=Vance |publisher=Herald Wheels |title=Wheels Classic Cars: The American Motors Pacer |date=29 January 2013 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> Its \"styling was different and appealing in an offbeat sort of way\" featuring large amounts of glass.<ref name=\"vance-pacer\"/> The Pacer's low beltline prevented the side door window from lowering completely out of sight, so Teague designed the inner door panels with large bolsters.\"<ref name=\"vance-pacer\"/> [[Anatole Lapine]], the designer of the [[Porsche 928]] body was inspired by the Pacer.<ref name=\"hubgarage\"/>\n\nTeague received AMC Hall of Fame recognition as the 2012 \"Person of American Motors\" - an executive or employee of American Motors or subsidiary company that was instrumental to the success of the company.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://carnutdirect.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=72&Itemid=89 |title=The American Motors Hall of Fame |publisher=CarNutDirect.com |year=2012 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Teague designs==\n[[File:1968 AMC AMX-GT Show Car \"Second Type\" 2.jpg|thumb|1968 AMX-GT show car]]\n[[File:1970 AMC AMX 390 go-package blue front.jpg|thumb|1970 AMC AMX 390 go-package blue front]]\n[[File:1973 AMC American Motors hornet 258 2 door hatchback fastback Beast.jpg|thumb|1973 AMC/American Motors Hornet 2-Door Fastback]]\n[[File:74MatadorXCoupe.JPG|thumb|1974 Matador X Coupe]]\n[[File:1969 AMC Javelin SST pony car red99.jpg|thumb|1969 AMC Javelin SST]]\n\nBritish automotive writer [[G.N. Georgano|Nick Georgano]] devotes a chapter to Teague in the book titled ''The Art of the American Automobile: the Greatest Stylists and their Work'' describing individuals whose creative talents made a difference in production and custom automobiles since the 1930s.<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=oRwMv8iNP-MC&pg=PA121&dq=Richard+A.+Teague |pages=121\u2013122 |title=The automobile in American history and culture: a reference guide |first=Michael L. |last=Berger |publisher=Greenwood Press |year=2001 |isbn=9780313245589 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> According to the authors of the book,''Yesterday's Tomorrows: Past Visions of the American Future'', Teague was one of the people that \"helped to transport us into the future.\"<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=CsW34SciarAC&pg=PR12 |title=Yesterday's tomorrows: past visions of the American future |first=Joseph J. |last=Corn |first2=Brian |last2=Horrigan |first3=Katherine |last3=Chambers |publisher=Johns Hopkins University Press |year=1996 |page=xii |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> While serving as the chief stylist, Teague was called by ''Popular Mechanics'' to predict the design trends for automobiles in the 1960s.<ref>{{cite journal|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=390DAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA1-PA154&dq=Richard+A.+Teague |title=The Changing Automobile |pages=154, 159 |journal=Popular Mechanics |volume=103 |issue=2 |date=February 1955 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> Together with [[Brooks Stevens]], Teague presented ideas about future cars and vehicle technologies at the 1963 [[SAE International|SAE]] congress in Detroit.<ref name=\"predictions\">{{cite web|url= http://www.thetruthaboutcars.com/2011/11/forward-into-the-past-into-the-future-brooks-stevens-dick-teague-predict-the-1970s-from-1963/ |title=Forward Into the Past Into the Future \u2013 Brooks Stevens & Dick Teague Predict the 1970s from 1963 |publisher=The Truth About Cars |first=Ronnie |last=Schreiber |date=26 November 2011 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> Teague, \"who is generally considered to have been a bit of a maverick\" predicted an evolutionary process for automobiles that turned out to be right.<ref name=\"predictions\"/> Teague foretold improvements in conventional gasoline engines, while cars \"would have greater variety of style now that glass could be shaped, and better suspension systems\" In contrast to Stevens, Teague believed that the automobiles of 1970 would still be built to provide basic transportation, and not be \"a home on wheels\" powered by an advanced power plant \u201cthe size of a breadbox.\u201d<ref name=\"predictions\"/>\n\nDuring the early-1960s, Teague's styling team began developing an entirely new concept for AMC - a sporty [[fastback]] design.<ref name=\"tarpon-marlin\">{{cite web |url=http://auto.howstuffworks.com/1965-1967-amc-marlin1.htm |title=The Development of the AMC Tarpon and Marlin|author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide''|publisher=auto.howstuffworks.com|date=26 October 2007 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.marlinautoclub.com/create/TeaguesExplanation.htm |title=Marlin History: Dick Teague\u2019s Explanation of Pre-Marlin Sketches |first=Richard A. |last=Teague |journal=Car Life (reprinted  Fish Tales, Vol 9 No 2, June 2008 |date=March 1965 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> Teague knew that the automaker was just not willing to spend the millions of dollars needed for all-new tooling, his design team made imaginative use of existing tooling and create spin-offs from existing products.<ref name=\"tarpon-marlin\"/> The results were proposals for which Teague selected the names for both: the [[Rambler Tarpon|Tarpon]] show car and the production Marlin.<ref name=\"tarpon-marlin\"/> Although promoting the smaller version, Teague recalled that \"Abernethy had decided that instead of a 2+2 we would build a 3+3 sports-type car.\"<ref name=\"tarpon-marlin\"/>\n\nTeague was responsible for the design of several AMC and Jeep vehicles.<ref>{{cite journal|url= http://wardsautoworld.com/ar/auto_men_behind_magic/index.html |last=Winter |first=Drew |title=The men behind the magic |journal=Ward's AutoWorld |date=1 May 1996 |accessdate=27 August 2013}}</ref> He developed the [[AMC Gremlin|Gremlin]], [[AMC Pacer|Pacer]], [[AMC Matador|Matador coupe]], Rambler American, [[AMC Javelin]], and [[AMC AMX|AMX]] [[AMC Hornet|Hornet]], and subsequently adapted AMC's compact platform for the [[AMC Concord|Concord]], [[AMC Spirit|Spirit]] and [[AMC Eagle|Eagle]] models. He was also responsible for a number of [[concept cars]] and lobbied for the production of several, including the compact [[Rambler Tarpon|Tarpon]] that ultimately led to the large [[AMC Marlin|Marlin]]. He also lobbied for continuing the two-seat [[AMC AMX|AMX]] models after 1970.\n\nThe 1968 [[AMC AMX-GT|AMX GT]] was one of the Teague-designed concept cars which had some of their design elements incorporated into production models. For this short-wheelbase coupe he styled a truncated [[kammback]] tail which was then used on the 1970 Gremlin.<ref name=\"tail\">{{cite journal|last=Lund |first=Robert |title=How the Gremlin lost its tail |journal=Popular Mechanics |date=August 1970 |volume=134 |issue=2 |pages=88\u201391, 183|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=j9gDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA88&dq=richard+a.+teague |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> He also designed the \"Concept 80\" series of show cars, built on variations of existing AMC platforms as ideas for possible future models.\n\nPerhaps Teague's best effort ever was the \"handsome design\" of the 1970 AMX/3 that AMC developed with help on the chassis from Italian sports-car engineer [[Giotto Bizzarrini]] and road testing and development from [[BMW]].<ref name=\"stuffAMX\"/> Before he and his team of designers settled on the final design, a fiberglass pushmobile was made with the molds taken from the final clay mockup.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://blog.hemmings.com/index.php/tag/richard-teague/ |title= Daniel StrohlAMX/3 pushmobile found, replicas forthcoming? |first=Daniel |last=Strohl |publisher=Hemmings Daily|date=27 October 2007 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> The AMX/3 is one of the most unusual cars to come out of Detroit in the late-1960s featuring an internationally sourced components, a top speed of {{convert|160|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}, and potentially the [[Ford Pantera]] as its closest competitor.<ref name=\"conceptcarz-AMX3\">{{cite web|url= http://www.conceptcarz.com/vehicle/z1749/AMC-AMX-III.aspx |title=1970 AMC AMX III news, pictures, and information |publisher=conceptcarz |first=Daniel |last=Vaughan |date=May 2006 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> Teague was instrumental in moving the car to production at a reasonable cost, but upcoming U.S. bumper regulations and other issues would have inflated its price beyond volume viability.<ref name=\"conceptcarz-AMX3\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.socalamc.com/forum/index.php?topic=26.0 |title=Where are all the AMX3s? |publisher=So. Cal. AMC |year=2008 |accessdate=27 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305044357/http://www.socalamc.com/forum/index.php?topic=26.0 |archivedate=5 March 2016 }}</ref>\n\nTeague was responsible for the [[Jeep Cherokee (XJ)]] that was launched in the United States in 1983.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mtYmAQAAMAAJ&q=Teague+design+Jeep+Cherokee |page=255 |title=Art of the American automobile: the greatest stylists and their work |first=Nick |last=Georgano |authorlink=G.N. Georgano |year=1995 |publisher=Smithmark |isbn=9780831706777 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> He described the practical and utilitarian appearance of the new SUV: \"We didn't want to lose the flavor of the older Jeeps ... We wanted it to look like something you'd want to take into the rough country.\"<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eAAAAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA28&dq=Teague+Jeep+Cherokee+take+into+the+rough+country |title=Who's king of the hill?|first=Jim |last=Dunne |first2=Jack |last2=Keebler |journal=Popular Science |date=January 1984 |volume=225 |page=28 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> The design was unchanged and remained in production through 2001 and in China to 2005. The Cherokee XJ was described by one automotive magazine in 2009 as \"possibly the best SUV shape of all time\", and was the last Teague design to go into production.<ref>{{cite journal|url =http://www.automobilemag.com/features/news/20_greatest_cars/0604_jeep_cherokee/ |first=Robert|last=Cumberford|title=20 greatest cars |journal=Automobile Magazine |date=April 2009 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref>\n\nStarting in 1982, Teague worked on the first large cars sold by AMC since 1978, the [[front-wheel drive|front-drive]] sedan code named X-58, for introduction in late-1986.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Dunne |first=Jim |title=Inside Detroit |journal=Popular Mechanics |date=June 1986 |volume=163 |issue=8 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0OMDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA40&lpg=PA40&dq=code+X58+AMC |page=40 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> and a companion code named X-59, that was to debut for the 1988 model year.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=BusinessWeek|date=28 April 1986|title=Can American Motors shed its sad-sack image? |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oUw1AAAAMAAJ&q=A+two-+door+coupe,+the+X-59,+debuts+in+1988&redir_esc=y |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> He achieved a roomy interior in an aerodynamic design, and the two-door model was to have featured hidden headlamps,<ref name=\"Wards Automotive News\"/> but the coupe was never produced. [[Giorgetto Giugiaro]] penned the sharper-edged exterior design for the four-door sedan that went into production as the [[Eagle Premier]].\n\n==Historian and collector==\n[[File:AMC AMX3 Side.jpg|thumb|1970 AMX/3, a mid-engined car]]\n\nTeague was a noted automobile historian and collected classic and rare vehicles, as well as other auto memorabilia. He restored old cars as a hobby, including a 1904 Packard, one of the first produced, and had already owned 285 cars by 1970.<ref name=\"tail\"/> Teague was a 4-wheel drive enthusiast before AMC bought Jeep, he owned several World War II models.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Ward's Auto World |title=Jumpin' Jeep |pages=24\u201325 |volume= |year=1977 }}</ref> At retirement, he mentioned that he had owned \"400 or 500\" cars.<ref name=\"Wards Automotive News\"/> Teague's collection included a rare [[AMC AMX#AMX.2F3|AMX/3]]. It was donated to the [[San Diego Automotive Museum]] along with most of his papers.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.classicscars.com/chassis/iso.htm |title=ISO \u2013 Bizarrini chassis numbers |publisher=classicscars.com |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090521152825/http://www.classicscars.com/chassis/iso.htm |archivedate=21 May 2009 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* Chilton's ''[[Automotive Industries (magazine)|Automotive Industries]]'' magazine named Teague the 1976 \"Man of the Year\" for his designs and work on the [[AMC Pacer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amcpacer.com/images/kenosha/kenosha-28-teague.jpg |title=Image of the 1 February 1976 magazine cover |publisher=The Pacer Page |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> In the award's 12-year history, this was the first time an automotive stylist was so honored.<ref name=\"hyde125\">{{cite book|last=Hyde |first=Charles K. |title=Storied Independent Automakers: Nash, Hudson, and American Motors |publisher=Wayne State University Press |year=2009|page=217|isbn=978-0-8143-3446-1 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=PerGbKxOPZYC&pg=PA217&dq=Richard+Teague+award |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref>\n* Teague was honored with the [[EyesOn Design]] 1999 \"Lifetime Design Achievement Award\" for his accomplishments as an automotive designer.<ref name=\"coachbuilt\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Past Award Winners |url= http://www.eyeson.org/index.php/eyeson/as-past-winners/P10/ |publisher=Detroit Institute of Ophthalmology |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110726050250/http://www.eyeson.org/index.php/eyeson/as-past-winners/P10/ |archivedate=26 July 2011 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theautochannel.com/news/press/date/19990618/press025296.html |title=Richard A. Teague to be Honored at 'Eyes on Design' |publisher=The Auto Channel |date=19 June 1999 |accessdate=21 May 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nRichard Teague married his wife Marian, in 1950. He had 3 children: Rick, Jeff, and daughter Lisa(Scarpelli).Teague's son, [[Jeff Teague (automotive designer)|Jeff Teague]], is also an industrial designer<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.smartfellowspress.com/killing_the_goose_21.htm |last=Garrison |first=Jasper |title=Killing the Goose, Chapter 21: Taurus |publisher=Smartfellows Press |accessdate=27 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205003020/http://www.smartfellowspress.com/killing_the_goose_21.htm |archivedate=5 February 2012 }}</ref> and established two automotive and product design services firms: \"Teague Design\" and \"JTDNA Design\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.teaguedesigninc.com/my-Profile.html |title=Profile |publisher=Teague Design |accessdate=27 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120508230102/http://www.teaguedesigninc.com/my-Profile.html |archivedate=8 May 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jtdna.com/aboutme.html |title=Jeff W Teague / Chief Executive Officer |publisher=JTDNA |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110208085628/http://jtdna.com/ |archivedate=8 February 2011 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> Jeff Teague \"doesn't long for the vehicles of his father's days\", but has sketched updated versions of his father's designs that include the AMX/3.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.asme.org/kb/news---articles/articles/automotive-design/car-designing--past-and-present |title=Car Designing Past and Present |first=Eric |last=Butterman |publisher=ASME.org |date=January 2013 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nRichard Teague died on 5 May 1991 after suffering a long illness.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book |first=Beverly|last=Kimes| title=Packard: A History of the Motor Car and the Company|publisher=Automobile Quarterly|year=2005|isbn=978-0-9711468-1-5}}\n* {{cite book |first=Michael|last=Lamm|first2=Dave|last2=Holls|title=A Century of Automotive Style: 100 Years of American Car Design|publisher=Lamm-Morada|year=1996|isbn=978-0-932128-07-2}}\n* {{cite book |first=Larry|last=Mitchell| title=AMC Muscle Cars|publisher=Motorbooks|year=2000|isbn=978-0-7603-0761-8}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.brophy.com/eodweb/htmls/designers/hd99_1.htm |title=Richard A. Teague: A friend writes of Teague's warmth, ability, and ingenuity |publisher=Brophy Marketing Services |quote=1999 Lifetime Design Achievement Award |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080511144724/http://www.brophy.com/eodweb/htmls/designers/hd99_1.htm |archivedate=11 May 2008 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.suninternational-usa.com/PPG-1.html |title=Teague's masterly job on a AMC/Renault Pace Car |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081005083005/http://www.suninternational-usa.com/PPG-1.html |archivedate=5 October 2008 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.idsa.org/category/reserved-tags/richard-teague |title=Richard A. Teague |publisher=Industrial Designers Society of America (IDSA) |accessdate=27 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130909020124/http://www.idsa.org/category/reserved-tags/richard-teague |archivedate=9 September 2013 }}\n\n{{American Motors}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Teague, Richard}}\n[[Category:People in the automobile industry]]\n[[Category:American automobile designers]]\n[[Category:American industrial designers]]\n[[Category:American Motors people]]\n[[Category:Chrysler designers]]\n[[Category:1923 births]]\n[[Category:1991 deaths]]\n[[Category:Packard people]]\n[[Category:Susan Miller Dorsey High School alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name           = Richard A. Teague\n| image          = Richard A Teague Foto.jpg\n| image_size     = \n| alt            = Man in a suit looking at camera while sitting at a desk\n| caption        = Richard Teague at AMC during the 1970s\n| birth_name     = \n| birth_date     = {{Birth date|1923|12|26}}\n| birth_place    = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], United States\n| death_date     = {{Death date and age|1991|05|05|1923|12|26}}<ref name=\"cp34\">{{cite journal|title=Obituaries |journal=Cars & Parts |publisher=Amos Press |volume=34 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=PkxWAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Richard+Teague%22+AMC |accessdate=27 August 2013}}</ref>\n| death_place    = [[San Diego]], California, United States\n| death_cause    = \n| education      = \n| alma_mater     = [[ArtCenter College of Design]]\n| occupation     = Industrial designer\n| years_active   = 1948\u20131983\n| employer       = [[General Motors]]<br/>[[Packard Motor Car Company]]<br/>[[Chrysler Corporation]]<br/>[[American Motors Corporation]]\n| known_for      = Developing the concept of interchangeable body panels for use among different models\n| notable_works  = 1955 [[Packard Patrician#1955\u20131956|Packard]]<br/>[[Oldsmobile#1950s styling|Oldsmobile Rocket]]<br/>[[Rambler Classic]]<br/>[[AMC Cavalier]]<br/>[[AMC Gremlin]]<br/>[[AMC Javelin]]<br/>[[AMC AMX]]<br/>[[AMC AMX-GT|AMX GT]]<br/>[[AMC Hornet]]<br/>[[AMC Eagle]]<br/>[[Jeep Cherokee (XJ)]]<br/>[[AMC Pacer]]\n| awards         = [[EyesOn Design]] Lifetime Design Achievement <br/> ''[[Automotive Industries (magazine)|Automotive Industries]] '' Man of the Year\n}}\n\n'''Richard A. \"Dick\" Teague''' (December 26, 1923 \u2013 May 5, 1991) was an American industrial designer in the North American automotive industry. He held [[automotive design]] positions at [[General Motors]], [[Packard]], and [[Chrysler]] before becoming Vice President of Design for [[American Motors|American Motors Corporation]] (AMC), and designed several notable show cars and production vehicles including AMC's [[AMC Pacer|Pacer]], [[AMC Gremlin|Gremlin]] and [[AMC Hornet|Hornet]] models, as well as the [[Jeep Cherokee (XJ)|Jeep Cherokee XJ]] and either designed assisted in the designing of later cars for Chrysler such as the [[Jeep Grand Cherokee]] and [[Dodge Neon|Neon]] after American Motors' buyout.\n\n==Early life==\nTeague's mother worked in the motion picture industry during the silent movie era.<ref name=\"aq1992\">{{cite journal|title=Dick Teague |journal=Automobile Quarterly |volume=30 |issue=2 |page=6 |year=1992 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=7D1WAAAAMAAJ&q=Dixie+Duval+Our+Gang |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> At five years of age Teague appeared in five episodes of ''[[Our Gang]]'', playing the role of Dixie Duval, a girl.<ref name=\"ward\">{{cite book|last=Ward |first=James Arthur |title=The fall of the Packard Motor Car Company |year=1995 |publisher=Stanford University Press |isbn=978-0-8047-2457-9 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=7D11a-EPzwMC&pg=PA177&dq=Richard+A.+Teague |page=177 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> When he was six, he was seriously injured in a car accident near [[Pasadena, California]], which was caused by a [[Driving under the influence|drunk driver]]. He lost several teeth, suffered a broken jaw, as well as sight in his right eye (leaving him without depth perception or stereoscopic vision), while his mother was left an invalid.<ref name=\"aq1992\"/><ref name=\"coachbuilt\">{{cite web|url=http://www.coachbuilt.com/des/t/teague/teague.htm |title=Richard (Dick) A. Teague 1923\u20131991 |publisher=Coacbuilt |year=2004 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> A year later his father was killed in another automobile accident, also caused by a drunk driver.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Racina |first=Thom |title=Car Man |journal=Westways |year=1975 |volume=67 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=FdO2AAAAIAAJ&q=Teague+Pasadena+A+year+later+his+father+was+killed+in+an+automobile+accident |page=53 |publisher=Automobile Club of Southern California |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref>\n\nWhile attending grade school in Los Angeles during the 1930s, Teague built model airplanes before turning to [[hot rod]]s, since his schoolmates included [[Ed Iskenderian|Ed Iskendarian (who became a drag racer)]], and land speed racer [[Stuart Hilborn]], as well as other car enthusiasts.<ref name=\"coachbuilt\"/><ref name=\"hubgarage\">{{cite web|url= http://www.hubgarage.com/mygarage/proto72/blogs/25991 |first=Adam |last=Icenogle |title=Richard Teague (1923 \u2013 1991) |publisher=Hub Garage |year=1998 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> He participated in time trials on a dry lake northeast of Los Angeles and was fond of saying that he \"had a little gasoline in his blood.\"<ref name=\"coachbuilt\"/>\n\nTeague was exempt from service in the armed forces during [[World War II]] because of his visual impairment.<ref name=\"ward\"/> After graduating from [[Susan Miller Dorsey High School]] in 1942, he worked as an aircraft technical illustrator for [[Northrop Corporation]].<ref name=\"coachbuilt\"/> His boss, Paul Browne, was a former designer at [[General Motors]] who suggested that Teague take night classes at the [[ArtCenter College of Design]].\n\n==Early work==\n[[File:Packard Executive Hardtop 1956.jpg|thumb|The last Teague design for Packard, the [[Packard Executive|Executive]]]]\nAfter [[World War II]], Teague penned a design for a pre-[[Henry J]] economy car for [[Kaiser Motors]]. In 1947 he joined the General Motors design studios<ref name=\"ward\"/> headed by Edmund Anderson. Starting as an [[apprentice]] stylist and eventually graduating to the [[Cadillac]] advanced design group, he also worked on the 1950 [[Oldsmobile#1950s styling|Oldsmobile Rocket]]. The 1950s \"saw some of the most beautiful and some of the most outlandish vehicles\" and the head of the design department at General Motors liked chrome on cars.<ref name=\"earl\">{{cite news|url= http://apps.detnews.com/apps/history/index.php?id=101 |last=Baulch |first=Vivian M. |title=Harley Earl, father of the 'dream' car |newspaper=The Detroit News |date=25 September 1998 |archiveurl= https://archive.is/20120808112650/http://apps.detnews.com/apps/history/index.php?id=101 |archivedate=8 August 2012 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> Teague described how two sets of overlay designs were made for [[Harley Earl]] to choose from. Both chrome trim sets had been put on one Oldsmobile prototype by mistake. Earl saw it and ordered it produced that way although the stylists were horrified.<ref name=\"earl\"/>\n\nTeague was dismissed from General Motors in 1952, and joined the [[Packard|Packard Motor Car Company]]<ref name=\"ward\"/> as Chief Stylist, following John Reinhart's resignation. His first work there was a minor facelift on the Packard line for 1953, and when the Packard management under [[James J. Nance]] decided to re-launch the Clipper brand as a stand-alone make, separate from Packard, it was Teague who achieved the visual distinction between the two. He also designed several Packard [[show car]]s.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/13/automobiles/collectibles/13LIST.html |title=Packard Dreams: The 7 Postwar Concept Cars |first=Fred|last=Hailer|newspaper=The New York Times |date=10 September 2009 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> These included the 1953 Balboa<ref name=\"dorrington\">{{cite journal|url= http://www.autoquarterly.com/featured_articles/article.php?id=9 |title=Packard Conceptualized |first=Leigh |last=Dorrington |journal=Automobile Quarterly |volume=50 |issue=1 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> (whose canopied reverse-slant and lowering for ventilation rear window<ref>{{cite journal|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=JNwDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA97&lpg=PA97&dq=Hudson+and+Packard+Present+Their+Cars+of+the+Future |page=97 |title=Hudson and Packard Present Their Cars of the Future |journal=Popular Mechanics |date=November 1953 |volume=100 |issue=5 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> later appeared on the 1957 [[Mercury Turnpike Cruiser]], 1958\u20131960 [[Lincoln Continental]], and various Mercury models), the 1954 Panther,<ref name=\"dorrington\"/> and contributed with William Schmidt to the 1955 Request, whose principal designer was Dick Macadam.<ref name=\"dorrington\"/>\n\nThe restyled Packard line for 1955 showed Teague's keen eye for detail and his ability to produce significant changes based on limited budgets. However, the company was not doing well following the purchase of struggling [[Studebaker]] Corporation in 1954. The last Teague design for Packard was the [[Packard Executive|Executive]], introduced mid-1956 and derived from the Clipper Custom, launched just as sales of the luxury Packard line collapsed. Teague also designed the last Packard show car, the Predictor, plus a new Packard and Clipper lineup for 1957 that would have followed the general lines of the Predictor. The design was stillborn when the Detroit Packard operations were shut down completely in mid-1956. Lacking funds for all-new models, the Studebaker-Packard Corporation had to make use of existing and economical Studebaker designs. Working with little time and money, the stopgap 1957 Studebaker-based Packard models became known as \"Packardbakers.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://auto.howstuffworks.com/1957-1958-packardbaker.htm |title=1957\u20131958 Packardbaker |author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide''|publisher=auto.howstuffworks.com |date=31 October 2007 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> The 1957 Packard Clipper, popularly derided as \"a Studebaker wearing Packard makeup\", was designed largely by Teague, and was intended as a temporary stopgap to keep the brand going until the company's fortunes improved and a \"real\" Packard model could again be made.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://auto.howstuffworks.com/1957-1958-packardbaker1.htm |title=Design of the 1957\u20131958 Packardbaker |author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide'' |publisher=auto.howstuffworks.com |date=31 October 2007 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref>\n\nBy 1957, the entire Packard styling team had moved to [[Chrysler Corporation]] and Teague became Chief Stylist.<ref name=\"century\">{{cite book |title=A century of automotive style: 100 years of American car design |page=202 |first=Michael |last=Lamm |first2=Dave |last2=Holls |year=1996 |publisher=Lamm-Morada |isbn= 9780932128072 }}</ref> After leaving due to management conflicts, he went to work for an independent design firm on non-automotive assignments.\n\n==American Motors==\n[[File:1961 AMC PRfoto Designers.jpg|thumb|AMC designers, 1961: Teague stands by the scale model Rambler's left front fender]]\n<!-- FAIR USE of 1961 AMC PRfoto Designers.jpg: see image description page at http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:1961 AMC PRfoto Designers.jpg for rationale -->\n[[File:1967 Ambassador DPL conv top-down-winter-FL palm.jpg|thumb|1967 AMC Ambassador convertible]]\n[[File:AMC Pacer 1975-1978.jpg|thumb|AMC Pacer 1975]]\n[[File:XJ Mossgreen.png|thumb|One of Teague's best known designs, the Jeep Cherokee XJ 1983]]\n\nTeague joined [[American Motors Corporation]] (AMC) as a member of [[Edmund E. Anderson]]'s design team in 1959, and became principal designer when Anderson left in 1961. Teague's first assignment, according to designer James W. (Jim) Alexander, was to re-do the front sheetmetal on the 1961 [[AMC Ambassador|Ambassador]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=VO8mAQAAMAAJ&q=first+assignment,+according+to+designer+James+W.+(Jim)+Alexander,+was+to+re-do+the+front+sheetmetal+on+the+1961+Ambassador Lamm, p. 202. Retrieved on 27 August 2013]</ref> The first cars influenced by Teague's styling were the 1963 [[Rambler Classic]] and Ambassador, AMC's first all-new models since 1956.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.canada.com/nationalpost/news/driving/story.html?id=63b38ace-dd81-436e-a781-279b22f10aab |last=Vance |first=Bill |title=Classic kept AMC in the auto game: 1963 AMC Rambler Classic |newspaper=National Post |date=28 July 2006 |accessdate=27 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103122644/http://www.canada.com/nationalpost/news/driving/story.html?id=63b38ace-dd81-436e-a781-279b22f10aab |archivedate=3 November 2012 }}</ref> With the ascendancy of Teague in the early 1960s, \"AMC Styling began to be written of in a more positive manner\" within the industry and automotive press.<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=BPqI4GNSPNQC&pg=PR5&dq=Richard+A.+Teague |page=v |title=The Nash Styling Sketchbook |first=Patrick R. |last=Foster |publisher=Olde Milford Press |year=1998 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref>\n\nTeague was Vice President at the automaker from 1964 until he retired from AMC in 1983. At his retirement, he joked that the only [[Detroit, Michigan|Detroit]] auto company he had not worked for was [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]].<ref name=\"Wards Automotive News\">{{cite journal|first=David|last=Smith|title=Dick Teague Ends Record Tenure In Style |journal=Wards Automotive News |date=February 1985 |url= http://www.planethoustonamx.com/main/dick%20teague%20retires.htm |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101127012656/http://planethoustonamx.com/main/dick%20teague%20retires.htm |archivedate=27 November 2010 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref>\n\nAlthough he worked within tight budget restrictions at AMC, Teague sometimes referred to his times there as \"[[Camelot]]\". Designing several different cars from existing AMC stampings, he worked \"relative miracles\" compared to the spending norms in this industry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brophy.com/eodweb/htmls/designers/hd99_1.htm |title=Richard A. Teague: A friend writes of Teague's warmth, ability, and ingenuity |publisher=Brophy Marketing Services |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080511144724/http://www.brophy.com/eodweb/htmls/designers/hd99_1.htm |archivedate=11 May 2008 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref>  With little money to work with, he reconfigured the existing cars and parts in new ways.<ref name=\"hine\">{{cite book|last=Hine |first=Thomas |title=The Great Funk: Falling Apart and Coming Together (on a Shag Rug) in the Seventies |publisher=Farrar, Straus and Giroux |year=2007 |url= https://archive.org/details/greatfunkfalling0000hine |url-access=registration |quote=richard a. teague. |pages=[https://archive.org/details/greatfunkfalling0000hine/page/41 41]\u201342 |isbn=978-0-374-14839-3 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> For example, he incorporated the doors from AMC's large-sized automobiles into his design for the new 1964 compact [[Rambler American]].\n\nThe [[AMC Cavalier]] was one of the \"Project IV\" concept cars in the mid-1960s that demonstrated advanced techniques of interchangeable body panels and design [[symmetry]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Bell |first=Jonathan |title=Concept Car Design: Driving the Dream |publisher=Rotovision |year=2003 |page=67 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=REQgF0IomccC&pg=PA67&dq=AMC+Cavalier |isbn=978-2-88046-564-3 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> The right front and left rear fenders were identical, as well as the panels for doors, hood, and deck lid all interchanged. The [[automobile platform]]s designed by Teague featured numerous interchangeable door skins, glass, and more. For example, the front and rear bumpers on the 1970 AMC Hornet were made from the same stamping. This design talent yielded significant cost savings for the company.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Irwin |first=Robert W. |title=Detroit Listening Post |journal=Popular Mechanics |volume=126 |issue=3 |page=30 |date=September 1966 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=stMDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA30&dq=AMC+Cavalier |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref>\n\nTeague's work on the 1967-1969 [[AMC Ambassador]] proved that he \"could do more with less than most any other car designer around -- usually because he had to.\"<ref name=\"ambassador-67-68-69\">{{cite web|url= http://auto.howstuffworks.com/1967-1969-amc-ambassador.htm |title=1967, 1968, 1969 AMC Ambassador |author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide'' |publisher=auto.howstuffworks.com |date=27 November 2007 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> While the 1965 models were reskinned  and rode on a longer wheelbase, Teague \"came through handsomely with crisp, angular lines\" that helped the Ambassador achieve record sales.<ref name=\"ambassador-67-68-69\"/> The 1967 model year brought even greater change, in line with Roy Abernethy's longtime aim of matching Big Three models on most every front, including an all-new Ambassador that \"emerged as one of the decade's unsung good-lookers.\"<ref name=\"ambassador-67-68-69\"/>\n\nAfter a management change at AMC, Teague worked under [[Roy D. Chapin, Jr.]] who was also a [[sports car]] enthusiast.<ref name=\"mueller99\">{{cite book|last=Mueller |first=Mike |title=Motor City Muscle: The High-Powered History of the American Muscle Car |publisher=MBI Publishing |year=1997 |page=99 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZLP8kKL4w2kC&pg=PA101&dq=1968+Javelin+born+out+of+AMX |isbn=978-0-7603-0196-8 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> Teague developed production models that featured \"excitement\" such as the [[AMC Javelin|Javelin]]. This design evolved from two AMX prototypes that were part of the \"Project IV\" concept cars during 1966.<ref>Mueller, page 101.</ref> Other top executives, such as [[Robert B. Evans]], wanted Teague's two-seat [[AMC AMX|AMX]] design to be brought to the market \"very quickly.\"<ref name=\"mueller99\"/> Teague originated a non-running show car in late-1965 and since he was a \u201ctwo-seater kind of guy, the production American Motors AMX was his car.\"<ref name=\"stuffAMX\">{{cite web|url= http://auto.howstuffworks.com/american-motors-sports-cars.htm |author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide''|publisher=auto.howstuffworks.com |date=15 May 2007 |title=American Motors AMX |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> The new models offerings reflected AMC's strategy to shed its \"economy car\" image and appeal to a more youthful, performance-oriented market.<ref name=\"mueller99\"/>\n\nDuring the 1970s, \"only a handful of cars had real personalities, and many of those came from the smallest U.S. producer, American Motors\" under the direction of Teague.<ref name=\"hine\"/>\n\nWhen the automobile market was changing to a greater focus on quality and fuel efficiency, Teague characterized the work by his design team at AMC as \"we still want to make cars with charisma; cars that stand out from the pack ... the future means the large look inside, away from the claustrophobic.\"<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Chilton's Iron Age |page=130 |volume=223 |year=1980 |title=Automobile manufacturing |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=23JWAAAAMAAJ&q=Teague+Jeep+design&dq=Teague+Jeep+design |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref>\n\nTeague worked on the design of the 1975 AMC Pacer, the first car with [[cab forward]] design.<ref name=\"coachbuilt\"/> It was also the first 'wide-small' automobile that \"gave drivers the impression they were driving a conventional large American.\"<ref name=\"vance-pacer\">{{cite web|url= http://thechronicleherald.ca/wheelsnews/570822-wheels-classic-cars-the-american-motors-pacer |first=Bill |last=Vance |publisher=Herald Wheels |title=Wheels Classic Cars: The American Motors Pacer |date=29 January 2013 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> Its \"styling was different and appealing in an offbeat sort of way\" featuring large amounts of glass.<ref name=\"vance-pacer\"/> The Pacer's low beltline prevented the side door window from lowering completely out of sight, so Teague designed the inner door panels with large bolsters.\"<ref name=\"vance-pacer\"/> [[Anatole Lapine]], the designer of the [[Porsche 928]] body was inspired by the Pacer.<ref name=\"hubgarage\"/>\n\nTeague received AMC Hall of Fame recognition as the 2012 \"Person of American Motors\" - an executive or employee of American Motors or subsidiary company that was instrumental to the success of the company.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://carnutdirect.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=72&Itemid=89 |title=The American Motors Hall of Fame |publisher=CarNutDirect.com |year=2012 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Teague designs==\n[[File:1968 AMC AMX-GT Show Car \"Second Type\" 2.jpg|thumb|1968 AMX-GT show car]]\n[[File:1970 AMC AMX 390 go-package blue front.jpg|thumb|1970 AMC AMX 390 go-package blue front]]\n[[File:1973 AMC American Motors hornet 258 2 door hatchback fastback Beast.jpg|thumb|1973 AMC/American Motors Hornet 2-Door Fastback]]\n[[File:74MatadorXCoupe.JPG|thumb|1974 Matador X Coupe]]\n[[File:1969 AMC Javelin SST pony car red99.jpg|thumb|1969 AMC Javelin SST]]\n\nBritish automotive writer [[G.N. Georgano|Nick Georgano]] devotes a chapter to Teague in the book titled ''The Art of the American Automobile: the Greatest Stylists and their Work'' describing individuals whose creative talents made a difference in production and custom automobiles since the 1930s.<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=oRwMv8iNP-MC&pg=PA121&dq=Richard+A.+Teague |pages=121\u2013122 |title=The automobile in American history and culture: a reference guide |first=Michael L. |last=Berger |publisher=Greenwood Press |year=2001 |isbn=9780313245589 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> According to the authors of the book,''Yesterday's Tomorrows: Past Visions of the American Future'', Teague was one of the people that \"helped to transport us into the future.\"<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=CsW34SciarAC&pg=PR12 |title=Yesterday's tomorrows: past visions of the American future |first=Joseph J. |last=Corn |first2=Brian |last2=Horrigan |first3=Katherine |last3=Chambers |publisher=Johns Hopkins University Press |year=1996 |page=xii |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> While serving as the chief stylist, Teague was called by ''Popular Mechanics'' to predict the design trends for automobiles in the 1960s.<ref>{{cite journal|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=390DAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA1-PA154&dq=Richard+A.+Teague |title=The Changing Automobile |pages=154, 159 |journal=Popular Mechanics |volume=103 |issue=2 |date=February 1955 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> Together with [[Brooks Stevens]], Teague presented ideas about future cars and vehicle technologies at the 1963 [[SAE International|SAE]] congress in Detroit.<ref name=\"predictions\">{{cite web|url= http://www.thetruthaboutcars.com/2011/11/forward-into-the-past-into-the-future-brooks-stevens-dick-teague-predict-the-1970s-from-1963/ |title=Forward Into the Past Into the Future \u2013 Brooks Stevens & Dick Teague Predict the 1970s from 1963 |publisher=The Truth About Cars |first=Ronnie |last=Schreiber |date=26 November 2011 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> Teague, \"who is generally considered to have been a bit of a maverick\" predicted an evolutionary process for automobiles that turned out to be right.<ref name=\"predictions\"/> Teague foretold improvements in conventional gasoline engines, while cars \"would have greater variety of style now that glass could be shaped, and better suspension systems\" In contrast to Stevens, Teague believed that the automobiles of 1970 would still be built to provide basic transportation, and not be \"a home on wheels\" powered by an advanced power plant \u201cthe size of a breadbox.\u201d<ref name=\"predictions\"/>\n\nDuring the early-1960s, Teague's styling team began developing an entirely new concept for AMC - a sporty [[fastback]] design.<ref name=\"tarpon-marlin\">{{cite web |url=http://auto.howstuffworks.com/1965-1967-amc-marlin1.htm |title=The Development of the AMC Tarpon and Marlin|author=Auto Editors of ''Consumer Guide''|publisher=auto.howstuffworks.com|date=26 October 2007 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.marlinautoclub.com/create/TeaguesExplanation.htm |title=Marlin History: Dick Teague\u2019s Explanation of Pre-Marlin Sketches |first=Richard A. |last=Teague |journal=Car Life (reprinted  Fish Tales, Vol 9 No 2, June 2008 |date=March 1965 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> Teague knew that the automaker was just not willing to spend the millions of dollars needed for all-new tooling, his design team made imaginative use of existing tooling and create spin-offs from existing products.<ref name=\"tarpon-marlin\"/> The results were proposals for which Teague selected the names for both: the [[Rambler Tarpon|Tarpon]] show car and the production Marlin.<ref name=\"tarpon-marlin\"/> Although promoting the smaller version, Teague recalled that \"Abernethy had decided that instead of a 2+2 we would build a 3+3 sports-type car.\"<ref name=\"tarpon-marlin\"/>\n\nTeague was responsible for the design of several AMC and Jeep vehicles.<ref>{{cite journal|url= http://wardsautoworld.com/ar/auto_men_behind_magic/index.html |last=Winter |first=Drew |title=The men behind the magic |journal=Ward's AutoWorld |date=1 May 1996 |accessdate=27 August 2013}}</ref> He developed the [[AMC Gremlin|Gremlin]], [[AMC Pacer|Pacer]], [[AMC Matador|Matador coupe]], Rambler American, [[AMC Javelin]], and [[AMC AMX|AMX]] [[AMC Hornet|Hornet]], and subsequently adapted AMC's compact platform for the [[AMC Concord|Concord]], [[AMC Spirit|Spirit]] and [[AMC Eagle|Eagle]] models. He was also responsible for a number of [[concept cars]] and lobbied for the production of several, including the compact [[Rambler Tarpon|Tarpon]] that ultimately led to the large [[AMC Marlin|Marlin]]. He also lobbied for continuing the two-seat [[AMC AMX|AMX]] models after 1970.\n\nThe 1968 [[AMC AMX-GT|AMX GT]] was one of the Teague-designed concept cars which had some of their design elements incorporated into production models. For this short-wheelbase coupe he styled a truncated [[kammback]] tail which was then used on the 1970 Gremlin.<ref name=\"tail\">{{cite journal|last=Lund |first=Robert |title=How the Gremlin lost its tail |journal=Popular Mechanics |date=August 1970 |volume=134 |issue=2 |pages=88\u201391, 183|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=j9gDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA88&dq=richard+a.+teague |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> He also designed the \"Concept 80\" series of show cars, built on variations of existing AMC platforms as ideas for possible future models.\n\nPerhaps Teague's best effort ever was the \"handsome design\" of the 1970 AMX/3 that AMC developed with help on the chassis from Italian sports-car engineer [[Giotto Bizzarrini]] and road testing and development from [[BMW]].<ref name=\"stuffAMX\"/> Before he and his team of designers settled on the final design, a fiberglass pushmobile was made with the molds taken from the final clay mockup.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://blog.hemmings.com/index.php/tag/richard-teague/ |title= Daniel StrohlAMX/3 pushmobile found, replicas forthcoming? |first=Daniel |last=Strohl |publisher=Hemmings Daily|date=27 October 2007 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> The AMX/3 is one of the most unusual cars to come out of Detroit in the late-1960s featuring an internationally sourced components, a top speed of {{convert|160|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}, and potentially the [[Ford Pantera]] as its closest competitor.<ref name=\"conceptcarz-AMX3\">{{cite web|url= http://www.conceptcarz.com/vehicle/z1749/AMC-AMX-III.aspx |title=1970 AMC AMX III news, pictures, and information |publisher=conceptcarz |first=Daniel |last=Vaughan |date=May 2006 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> Teague was instrumental in moving the car to production at a reasonable cost, but upcoming U.S. bumper regulations and other issues would have inflated its price beyond volume viability.<ref name=\"conceptcarz-AMX3\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.socalamc.com/forum/index.php?topic=26.0 |title=Where are all the AMX3s? |publisher=So. Cal. AMC |year=2008 |accessdate=27 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305044357/http://www.socalamc.com/forum/index.php?topic=26.0 |archivedate=5 March 2016 }}</ref>\n\nTeague was responsible for the [[Jeep Cherokee (XJ)]] that was launched in the United States in 1983.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mtYmAQAAMAAJ&q=Teague+design+Jeep+Cherokee |page=255 |title=Art of the American automobile: the greatest stylists and their work |first=Nick |last=Georgano |authorlink=G.N. Georgano |year=1995 |publisher=Smithmark |isbn=9780831706777 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> He described the practical and utilitarian appearance of the new SUV: \"We didn't want to lose the flavor of the older Jeeps ... We wanted it to look like something you'd want to take into the rough country.\"<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eAAAAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA28&dq=Teague+Jeep+Cherokee+take+into+the+rough+country |title=Who's king of the hill?|first=Jim |last=Dunne |first2=Jack |last2=Keebler |journal=Popular Science |date=January 1984 |volume=225 |page=28 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> The design was unchanged and remained in production through 2001 and in China to 2005. The Cherokee XJ was described by one automotive magazine in 2009 as \"possibly the best SUV shape of all time\", and was the last Teague design to go into production.<ref>{{cite journal|url =http://www.automobilemag.com/features/news/20_greatest_cars/0604_jeep_cherokee/ |first=Robert|last=Cumberford|title=20 greatest cars |journal=Automobile Magazine |date=April 2009 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref>\n\nStarting in 1982, Teague worked on the first large cars sold by AMC since 1978, the [[front-wheel drive|front-drive]] sedan code named X-58, for introduction in late-1986.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Dunne |first=Jim |title=Inside Detroit |journal=Popular Mechanics |date=June 1986 |volume=163 |issue=8 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0OMDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA40&lpg=PA40&dq=code+X58+AMC |page=40 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> and a companion code named X-59, that was to debut for the 1988 model year.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=BusinessWeek|date=28 April 1986|title=Can American Motors shed its sad-sack image? |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oUw1AAAAMAAJ&q=A+two-+door+coupe,+the+X-59,+debuts+in+1988&redir_esc=y |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> He achieved a roomy interior in an aerodynamic design, and the two-door model was to have featured hidden headlamps,<ref name=\"Wards Automotive News\"/> but the coupe was never produced. [[Giorgetto Giugiaro]] penned the sharper-edged exterior design for the four-door sedan that went into production as the [[Eagle Premier]].\n\n==Historian and collector==\n[[File:AMC AMX3 Side.jpg|thumb|1970 AMX/3, a mid-engined car]]\n\nTeague was a noted automobile historian and collected classic and rare vehicles, as well as other auto memorabilia. He restored old cars as a hobby, including a 1904 Packard, one of the first produced, and had already owned 285 cars by 1970.<ref name=\"tail\"/> Teague was a 4-wheel drive enthusiast before AMC bought Jeep, he owned several World War II models.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Ward's Auto World |title=Jumpin' Jeep |pages=24\u201325 |volume= |year=1977 }}</ref> At retirement, he mentioned that he had owned \"400 or 500\" cars.<ref name=\"Wards Automotive News\"/> Teague's collection included a rare [[AMC AMX#AMX.2F3|AMX/3]]. It was donated to the [[San Diego Automotive Museum]] along with most of his papers.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.classicscars.com/chassis/iso.htm |title=ISO \u2013 Bizarrini chassis numbers |publisher=classicscars.com |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090521152825/http://www.classicscars.com/chassis/iso.htm |archivedate=21 May 2009 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* Chilton's ''[[Automotive Industries (magazine)|Automotive Industries]]'' magazine named Teague the 1976 \"Man of the Year\" for his designs and work on the [[AMC Pacer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amcpacer.com/images/kenosha/kenosha-28-teague.jpg |title=Image of the 1 February 1976 magazine cover |publisher=The Pacer Page |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> In the award's 12-year history, this was the first time an automotive stylist was so honored.<ref name=\"hyde125\">{{cite book|last=Hyde |first=Charles K. |title=Storied Independent Automakers: Nash, Hudson, and American Motors |publisher=Wayne State University Press |year=2009|page=217|isbn=978-0-8143-3446-1 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=PerGbKxOPZYC&pg=PA217&dq=Richard+Teague+award |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref>\n* Teague was honored with the [[EyesOn Design]] 1999 \"Lifetime Design Achievement Award\" for his accomplishments as an automotive designer.<ref name=\"coachbuilt\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Past Award Winners |url= http://www.eyeson.org/index.php/eyeson/as-past-winners/P10/ |publisher=Detroit Institute of Ophthalmology |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110726050250/http://www.eyeson.org/index.php/eyeson/as-past-winners/P10/ |archivedate=26 July 2011 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theautochannel.com/news/press/date/19990618/press025296.html |title=Richard A. Teague to be Honored at 'Eyes on Design' |publisher=The Auto Channel |date=19 June 1999 |accessdate=21 May 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nRichard Teague married his wife Marian, in 1950. He had 3 children: Rick, Jeff, and daughter Lisa(Scarpelli).Teague's son, [[Jeff Teague (automotive designer)|Jeff Teague]], is also an industrial designer<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.smartfellowspress.com/killing_the_goose_21.htm |last=Garrison |first=Jasper |title=Killing the Goose, Chapter 21: Taurus |publisher=Smartfellows Press |accessdate=27 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205003020/http://www.smartfellowspress.com/killing_the_goose_21.htm |archivedate=5 February 2012 }}</ref> and established two automotive and product design services firms: \"Teague Design\" and \"JTDNA Design\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.teaguedesigninc.com/my-Profile.html |title=Profile |publisher=Teague Design |accessdate=27 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120508230102/http://www.teaguedesigninc.com/my-Profile.html |archivedate=8 May 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jtdna.com/aboutme.html |title=Jeff W Teague / Chief Executive Officer |publisher=JTDNA |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110208085628/http://jtdna.com/ |archivedate=8 February 2011 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref> Jeff Teague \"doesn't long for the vehicles of his father's days\", but has sketched updated versions of his father's designs that include the AMX/3.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.asme.org/kb/news---articles/articles/automotive-design/car-designing--past-and-present |title=Car Designing Past and Present |first=Eric |last=Butterman |publisher=ASME.org |date=January 2013 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nRichard Teague died on 5 May 1991 after suffering a long illness.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book |first=Beverly|last=Kimes| title=Packard: A History of the Motor Car and the Company|publisher=Automobile Quarterly|year=2005|isbn=978-0-9711468-1-5}}\n* {{cite book |first=Michael|last=Lamm|first2=Dave|last2=Holls|title=A Century of Automotive Style: 100 Years of American Car Design|publisher=Lamm-Morada|year=1996|isbn=978-0-932128-07-2}}\n* {{cite book |first=Larry|last=Mitchell| title=AMC Muscle Cars|publisher=Motorbooks|year=2000|isbn=978-0-7603-0761-8}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.brophy.com/eodweb/htmls/designers/hd99_1.htm |title=Richard A. Teague: A friend writes of Teague's warmth, ability, and ingenuity |publisher=Brophy Marketing Services |quote=1999 Lifetime Design Achievement Award |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080511144724/http://www.brophy.com/eodweb/htmls/designers/hd99_1.htm |archivedate=11 May 2008 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.suninternational-usa.com/PPG-1.html |title=Teague's masterly job on a AMC/Renault Pace Car |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081005083005/http://www.suninternational-usa.com/PPG-1.html |archivedate=5 October 2008 |accessdate=27 August 2013 }}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.idsa.org/category/reserved-tags/richard-teague |title=Richard A. Teague |publisher=Industrial Designers Society of America (IDSA) |accessdate=27 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130909020124/http://www.idsa.org/category/reserved-tags/richard-teague |archivedate=9 September 2013 }}\n\n{{American Motors}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Teague, Richard}}\n[[Category:People in the automobile industry]]\n[[Category:American automobile designers]]\n[[Category:American industrial designers]]\n[[Category:American Motor